cs.DL, cs.IR, cs.SI, cs.CY, cs.SD 

This paper discusses altmetrics, which are increasingly relevant in the digital age of scholarly communication. The paper focuses on the use of online tools and systems to measure scholarly impact, which is relevant to several sub-categories of computer science. Specifically, cs.DL (Digital Libraries) is the most likely sub-category, as altmetrics are closely related to the management and analysis of digital information. cs.IR (Information Retrieval) is also likely, as altmetrics involve the retrieval and analysis of information from online sources. cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) is relevant due to the use of social media platforms in altmetrics. cs.CY (Computers and Society) is relevant due to the implications of altmetrics for scholarly communication and evaluation. Finally, cs.SD (Software Development) is relevant due to the development of software tools for altmetric analysis.
